          "body": "Verse 13:4 is the chapter's positive center, and it is architecturally dense. Six imperative verbs define covenant loyalty: *follow* (halakh — walk behind as a disciple), *fear* (yare — reverent awe before the sovereign), *keep His commandments* (shamar mitsvot — guard and observe His commands), *listen to His voice* (shama beqolo — hear with intention to obey), *serve Him* (avad — labor as a covenant servant), *cling to Him* (davaq — cleave with the tenacity of marriage). These six verbs do not describe six discrete acts but one comprehensive covenantal posture — total person oriented toward total devotion. The Shema (6:4-5) is the heart; these six verbs are the body of what loving the LORD 'with all your heart and soul' looks like when walked out. Chuck Swindoll observes that Deuteronomy's genius is its relentless refusal to leave theology in the abstract — it always lands in verbs, in postures, in actions."
